<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06161180 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06161180 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  FAMILY; CHILDREN; MEXICO; CLUB; TRIP; TRAVEL  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The allure was great: Club Med, that renowned retreat for lustful yuppies, hasfollowed a generation into the staid responsibilities of parenthood. Now,instead of wanton cheerleaders and conga lines on the beach it has, well,child care. Select Club Med villages offer family vacations where thegrown-ups relax &quot;while the little ones frolic with others their own age.&quot; Itsounded ideal to two San Jose couples who wanted their kids along, but agenuine break, too. If nothing else, for a few hours each day, theseoatmeal-splattered warriors could reminisce.;    They decided on a week'svacation in Ixtapa on Mexico's southern coast, one of two Club Med villageswith programs for children under 2. Mercury News Staff Writer Jack Fischer andhis wife, physician Joyce Floyd, took their children, Molly, 4, and John, 23months. Cartoonist Scott Willis and his wife, Staff Writer Patricia Patterson,took their boys, Andrew, 3, and Daniel, 18 months.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  REAL FAMILY VACATIONSTODDLING OFF TO CLUB MED WITH THE KIDS ANDPROMISES OF FREEDOM  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Family Vacation SpecialSee related stories pages 1T and 6-9T of this section.  </MEMO><TEXT>     They knew enough about Club Med to be prepared for sparse rooms and rah-rahstuff. What they didn't know was what to expect from the Kids Clubs. Wouldthey live up to their promise? The answer? Yes. And no. Here are their stories.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910609  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1T  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  214  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday June 9, 199100161180,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercur